#### You <b>MUST</b> write all comments using the single line format.

Writing single line comments, means all comments are stripped out when tasks build/dev tasks are run.

*Bad Example*

	.box {
		background: red; /* Your Comment */
	}

*Good Example*

	.box {
		background: red; // Your Comment
	}

#### You <b>SHOULD</b> write your comments in specific formats based on the context within your codebase

Commenting in your codebase is very important for communication, as well seperation of modules and providing notes which are relevant for how/what a piece of functionality does/is.

When defining new modules, modifiers or sectioning partials, it is recommended you use the following format.

	// =============================
	// Base Flag Pattern Styling
	// =============================

If you are creating patterns or functionality, which needs to be shown in a visual manner, you <b>COULD</b> provide provide diagrams, like the following;

	//
	//    Flag Sidebar               Flag Body
	//
	//                          ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~
	//                          ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~
	//    ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~           ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~
	//    ~         ~           ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~
	//    ~         ~           ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~
	//    ~         ~           ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~
	//    ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~           ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~
	//                          ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~
	//                          ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~
	//

Lastly, when it comes to commenting constructs such as mixins and functions, it is recommended you provide commenting for both example use and parameter descriptions;

	//
	// Example Use:
	//
	// @include rem-sizing("font-size", 32px);
	//
	// Parameter Description:
	//
	// $property - A string value which contains the property which you want to set a REM unit value for. // "font-size"
	// $value    - The value (in pixels) of the elements property you are setting the REM value for.      // 12px
	// $context  - This value is mapped back to the $font-size-base variable set within the _settings.scss partial.
	//

<br />

#### You <b>SHOULD</b> include comments which communicate a specific feature or decision back to your team

If you implement a certain feature which you feel needs to be explained to maintainers to understand why it has been done a certain way, it is recommended that you provide a comment/s

If this is a specific part of a declaration, please include a comment at the end of the property in the following format:

*Example:*

	.box {
	       background-color: red; // Your comment
	}

*Note: if the codebase is legacy and does not support Sass commenting, please replace with the general CSS comment approach*

If the comment is required for whole declaration blocks, please include the comment above the block, like so:

*Example:*

	// Your comment here

	.box {
	       background-color: red;
	}

<br />
